title: zold_out
body:
A tactical gacha RPG with deckbuilding mechanics for mobile platforms and PC, developed and currently published by Hong Kong-based developer company C4Cat Entertainment, and previously published by Chinese publisher NetEase. Initially a Kickstarter project from 2017, it received an initial release in Japan as "Zold:Out～鍛冶屋の物語"[tn]"Zold:Out~A Blacksmith's Tale"[/tn] by NetEase in 2020, before shutting down in 2022. C4Cat would later release the game in Chinese in 2021, and globally (subsequently relaunching JP) in 2023.

It follows the story of two young men: a blacksmith named Helide and a merchant named Oscar. Together with Helide's mysterious maid Lorna, elven lover-of-cuteness Mamie, and later enigmatic hunter Zelena, they go from place to place gathering materials and learning new techniques, all to pull Helide's weapons shop out of bankruptcy, while unwittingly getting involved in a conspiracy that may endanger the world peace that the two young men desire to protect.

title: silicon_creature_(blame!)

One of the main (human-originated) species in [[Blame!]].

Silicon creatures are cybernetic organisms at war with the humans. One of their main traits is their emotions and temper, capables of feeling fury and curiosity. They have their own identities and personalities (even then, many are downright psychotic killing machines). Each one has its own distinctive look, but all of them are anthropomorphic, looking as females or males and often seen banded in male-female pairs.

Their Japanese name in the original manga is 珪素生物 ([i]keiso seibutsu[/i]), which is actually a general science fiction term for "Silicon-Based Life Forms":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothetical_types_of_biochemistry#Silicon_biochemistry].

title: kibasen
body:
Kibasen (lit. "Cavalry Battle") is a type of [[piggyback]] riding game played by school children in Japan. The sport is commonly played during annual school [[sports festival]]s.

The game consists of teams of four players, with one player from each team riding on top of the other three players. Teams are often divided into opposing red and white factions. The goal is to knock the opposing team's rider down, or more commonly, remove their [[bandana]]. 

A two person variation, commonly called a chicken fight, involves someone riding [[piggyback]] atop another's shoulders. 

Cavalry battles and chicken fights may be played on the ground or in a [[pool]]. Although chicken fights are seen as dangerous, cavalry battles are a common staple of Japanese school [[sports festival]]s.

title: double-barreled_shotgun
body:
A [[shotgun]] with 2 parallel barrels either aligned side by side (SxS) or over and under (O/U).

Commonly, they are operated with break-action and usually are [[sawed-off shotgun|sawed off]]. Early ones have two triggers, allowing firing either one or both shells at once while the later and modern models only have a single trigger capable of firing one and another in quick succession.

In media, they usually wielded in the wild west as coach guns, 18" to 24" barrels, but can also be seen during apocalypses like zombies or wastelands.
In games, Doom II marked it's debut as the Super Shotgun, a more devastating upgrade to the workhorse weapon, the shotgun, and has became a staple in the shooters genre.

title: balance_scale

Yojouhan Shinwa Taikei is a Japanese novel by [[Morimi Tomihiko]], originally published in December 2004 as a tankoubon and later re-published in March 2008 a bunkoban. title: m26_grenade
body:
The [b]M26[/b] is a fragmentation hand [b][[grenade]][/b] developed by the [[United States]] [[military]]. It entered service around 1952 and was first used in combat during the [[Korean War]]. Its distinct [[lemon]] shape led it to being nicknamed the "[[lemon]] grenade" (compare the [[Russia]]n/[[Soviet]] "F1 grenade":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-1_grenade_(Russia)], with similar nickname).

The grenade was developed as a result of studies on the [[mk2 grenade|Mk 2]]. The M26 series was created after [[World War II]] to meet criticisms of the Mk 2. It was replaced by the M33 series grenade (M33/"M67":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M67_grenade]) at the end of the [[Vietnam War]].

title: mk2_grenade
body:
The [b]Mk 2 grenade[/b] (Mk II) is a fragmentation-type anti-personnel hand [[grenade]] introduced by the [[United States]] [[military]] in 1918. It was the standard issue anti-personnel grenade used during [[World War II]], and also saw limited service in later conflicts, including the [[Korean War]] and [[Vietnam War]]. It replaced the failed Mk 1 grenade of 1917. The grooves and knobs gave the Mk 2 appearance of a [i][[pineapple]][/i], and are the origin of the nickname.

It was gradually phased out of service as the [[m26 grenade|M26]]-series grenade was introduced during the Korean War. Due to the tremendous quantity manufactured during WWII, the Mk 2 was still in limited issue with the [[united states army|US Army]] and [[united states marine corps|US Marine Corps]] throughout the 1950s and 1960s.

title: high_standard_model_10
body:
The [b]High Standard Model 10[/b] (HS10) is a 12-gauge gas operated, semi-automatic [b][[shotgun]][/b], manufactured by the "High Standard Manufacturing Company":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_Standard_Manufacturing_Company] of Hamden, Connecticut, [[united states|USA]]. It is easily recognized by its [b][[bullpup]][/b] design, rotatable shoulder stock, and integrated [[flashlight]]. The basic design of the HS10 was developed in the late 1950s by Alfred Crouch.

The concept of this shotgun was quite interesting to many [[police]] agencies who adopted the HS10 in the late 1960s and early 1970s. However, most of the agencies found many shortcomings, and ultimately ceased using it . The problems with HS10 was the failure to cycle correctly even with correct [[shotgun shells|rounds]], roughly unpredictable trigger feel, and the recoil that can damage flashlight [[battery|batteries]].

title: lahti_l-35
body:
The [b]Lahti L-35[/b] is a Finnish semi-automatic [b][[handgun]][/b] designed by [b]Aimo Lahti[/b] in 1929, produced between 1935 and 1952. Designed to be manufactured autonomously in Finland, the pistol was used by the [[Finnish text|Finnish]] [[military]] throughout the Winter War and Continuation War. The L-35 was well-manufactured and worked reliably in cold conditions or when fouled. The use of a bolt accelerator helped making it reliable.

Although the Lahti is outwardly similar to the [[Luger P08]], the firing mechanism is significantly different and more closely related to the [[Bergmann–Bayard pistol]]. The Lahti L-35 is a recoil operated, single-action, locked breech [[gun|firearm]] fitted with a concealed hammer. The pistol itself is well sealed from dirt and ice but is heavy by modern standards. The Swedish copy was dubbed the [b]Husqvarna Model 40[/b] or m/40.

h1. See also

This [[weapon]] was first publicly revealed in 2016. The only difference between the AK-12 and the AK-15 is their calibre.

title: beretta_m1934
body:
The [b]Beretta Model 1934[/b] is an Italian compact semi-automatic [b][[handgun]][/b], chambered in 9mm Corto (.380 ACP), manufactured by Fabbrica d'Armi Pietro Beretta from 1934 to 1991. It was designed and purpose-built for the Italian [[military]], issued on the beginning of 1934. 

The M1934 is a blowback-operated handgun. Standard [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] capacity is only 7 rounds. When the empty magazine is removed it no longer holds the slide back. The slide will come forward and close the gun unless it is held open by application of the safety, a separate operation, and this slows down the reloading of the pistol.

title: baroness_(g.i._joe)
body:
A fictional female character from the [[G.I. Joe]] toyline by [[Hasbro]], originally appearing in the [i]G.I. Joe[/i] comic series. 

[b]The Baroness[/b] is a villainess, associated with G.I. Joe's nemesis [[terrorist]] organization, [[Cobra Command]].

Baroness serves as Cobra's intelligence officer and capable lieutenant to [[Cobra Commander]]. With long black hair, black-rimmed glasses, and a black leather outfit, Baroness is a dark, sensual femme fatale whose beauty is matched only by her ruthlessness. 

Although the character was not part of the initial [i]G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero[/i] toyline release in 1982, she did appear in [i]G.I. Joe[/i] #1, published by [[Marvel]] Comics in June 1982 and was, in fact, the first character to cross over from the comics into the animated series and finally into the toy line. 

She made her debut as an action figure in the 1984 toy series, wearing a new dark uniform that was then carried back over to the comic and cartoon.

"Sienna Miller":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sienna_Miller portrays The Baroness as one of the primary antagonists of Stephen Sommers' 2009 live action film [i]"G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G.I._Joe:_The_Rise_of_Cobra [/i].

title: gunlord
body:
[b]Gunlord[/b] is a 2012 single-player run and gun [[video game]] developed and published by [[germany|German]] indie company NG:Dev.Team for the [[SNK]] [[Neo Geo]] MVS and the [[SEGA Dreamcast]]. 

It is the first run and gun title from NG:Dev.Team and their third game overall. 

Taking place after the events of a previous game called "Last Hope":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Last_Hope_(video_game), the player assumes the role of the titular [[gunlord_(character)|Gunlord]] facing against an evil lord called "The Master" on planet Kairos II while searching for his wife [[vanessa_(gunlord)|Vanessa]], who went missing after defeating the evil empire of the previous game. 

Inspired by 16-bit titles such as [[Contra]] and "Turrican":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turrican, the game originally started development in 2003 but was postponed for various years until the project was resumed in 2010, lasting eighteenth months in production.

Gunlord garnered positive reception from critics since its release; praise was given to the audiovisual presentation and exploration-based gameplay but criticism was geared towards several aspects such as the expansive level design, difficulty and technical issues on the Dreamcast version. An updated version with new content titled [[Gunlord X]] was later released for the [[Nintendo Switch]] and the [[PlayStation 4]].

title: mp28
body:
The [b]MP28[/b] or MP28/II is a German [b][[submachine gun]][/b], predominantly chambered in 9×19mm Parabellum. It was designed by Hugo Schmeisser in late 1920s as a post-[[World War I]] improvement on his earlier [[MP18]]. Manufactured by "C.G. Haenel":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C.G._Haenel] plant in Suhl, [[Germany]].

Albeit being similar to the earlier MP18, the main improvement over the MP18 was the inclusion of a fire selector device in the form of a cross-bolt switch above the trigger group, which could give [b]single shots or fully-automatic fire[/b]. The narrow recoil spring and guide rod of the MP18 was replaced by a wide diameter spring. The MP28 still utilized blowback, open-bolt mechanism. The [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] is inserted on the left side, standard capacity is 20 or 30-round. However, the MP28 does not accept the 32-round "snail" [[drum magazine]] of the [[luger p08|Artillery Luger]] anymore.

title: jackhammer
body:
A [b]jackhammer[/b] is a pneumatic or electro-mechanical [[tools|tool]] that combines a [[hammer]] directly with a [[chisel]]. It was invented by William Mcreavy, who then sold the patent to "Charles Brady King":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Brady_King]. Handheld jackhammers are generally powered by compressed air, but some are also powered by electric motors. Larger jackhammers, such as rig-mounted hammers used on [[construction]] [[machinery]], are usually hydraulically powered. These tools are typically used to break up [[rock]], [[pavement]], and concrete. 

It is known as [b]pneumatic drill[/b] or [b]demolition hammer[/b] in British English.

The [b]Armsel Striker[/b] is a 12-gauge [b]shotgun[/b] of [[South Africa]]n origin, designed for designed for [[rioting|riot]]control and [[combat shotgun|combat]]. It is also known as Sentinel Arms Co Striker-12, Protecta, Protecta Bulldog and SWD Street Sweeper. The weapon features a top-[[folding stock]], pistol grip, and a [[vertical foregrip]]. The most distinctive feature is its [b]revolving cylinder[/b], that has 12-[[shotgun shell|round]] capacity and 7-round on more compact variants.

It was initially designed by a Rhodesian national, Hilton R. Walker in 1981, who then emigrated to South Africa. He brought his design for the shotgun with him as well. A copy of the Striker was made by the US gunmaker Cobray and marketed as the SWD Street Sweeper from 1989 through 1993.

It was the next step from the [[Winchester Model 1897]] hammer-fired shotgun. The Model 1912 was designed by engineer "T.C. Johnson":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T.C._Johnson], and was based in part on the M1893/97 design by "John Browning":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Browning], in that it used a sliding forearm (pump action) to cycle the mechanism. The [[weapon]] was a very successful internal hammer pump-action shotgun.

title: sengoku_majin_goshogun
body:
[b]GoShogun[/b] (戦国魔神ゴーショーグン, [i]Sengoku Majin GōShōgun[/i]) is a [[super robot]] [[mecha]] anime series created by Shudo Takeshi. 

It was produced and aired in 1981 in Japan, with a movie special released in 1982 and a film sequel, [b]GoShogun: The Time Étranger[/b] or [b]Time Stranger[/b], in 1985. 

Its title has been variously translated into English as "Demon God of the War-Torn Land [[GoShogun]]", "Warring Demon God GoShogun", and "Civil War Devil-God GoShogun," but in the US and parts of Europe it is primarily known as [b]Macron 1[/b], the title of its North American adaptation.

The GoShogun series and its film sequel, The Time Étranger, were both written by Shudo Takeshi and directed by Yuyama Kunihiko. The series is noted for its witty dialogue and lighthearted parody of its own genre conventions.

The Time Étranger shifts away from the original genre, leaving the robot aside entirely to focus on the strong and complex heroine. It has been praised for its serious tone, psychological intensity, and handling of mature themes.

title: winchester_model_1200/1300
body:
The Winchester Model 1200 and Model 1300 are two series of [[pump action]] [b][[shotgun]]s[/b] that were manufactured by the Winchester-Western Division of "Olin Corporation":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olin_Corporation]. It was produced in 12-, 16- and 20-gauge. The military version of the 1200 has the ability to have a [[bayonet]] fixed. 

The [b]Winchester Model 1200[/b] was introduced in 1964 as a low-cost replacement for the [[Winchester Model 1912]]. It was used by [[united states marine corps|US Marines]] and [[united states army|US Army]] [[soldier]]s in [[vietnam war|Vietnam]]. Though the shotgun was well received, Winchester wanted to develop a 'cheaper' shotgun that would cut into the market of Remington & Mossberg. The Winchester Model 1200 was one of the models to be phased out, when the "USRAC":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Repeating_Arms_Company] acquired Winchester from Olin in 1980. The 1200 eventually ceased all production by 1981 and ceded the pump shotgun line to the Model 1300.

The [b]Winchester Model 1300[/b] first appeared in 1978 as an 'economy' version of the Model 1200 and ultimately took over the shotgun line for Winchester in 1981 when the 1200 was discontinued. In addition to the hunting/sporting variations, the Model 1300 has been sold worldwide as the Tactical [[Police]] model, Slug Hunter, Marine, and Stainless Security version. Now the 1300 has been discontinued by Winchester.

title: yew
body:
Yews are [[conifer]]ous [[tree]]s or shrubs in the Taxus family. They are slow-growing and very long-lived, and reach heights of 2.5–20 m (8.2–65.6 ft), with trunk girth averaging 5 m (16 ft). They have reddish bark, lanceolate, flat, dark-green leaves 10–40 mm (1⁄2–1+1⁄2 in) long and 2–3 mm (3⁄32–1⁄8 in) broad, arranged spirally on the stem, but with the leaf bases twisted to align the leaves in two flat rows either side of the stem.
The "cone" of a yew is a bright right berry-like fruit around a single seed.

title: conifer
body:
A plant, usually a [[tree]] or [[bush]], that is cone-bearing, usually perennial (keeps its leaves in [[snow]]), and needle leaved. Trees are often conical shaped with drooping branches. "Wikipedia page.":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conifer]

Individual species such as [[pine_tree]] exist within the genus.
Others include cypresses, [[spruce]]s, junipers, and [[yew]]s.
[[Christmas tree]]s are usually conifers.

A [[pinecone]] by itself or individual needle leaves alone do not get tagged, but a single [[branch]] of a coniferous plant may.

body:
Originally from Hindu mythology, the vajra is the [[weapon]] of the thunder god Indra (analagous to Thor's hammer Mjolnir in Norse mythology). It is a small, two-headed [[club (weapon)|]] with multiple prongs on each head, and symbolizes both the properties of a diamond (indestructibility) and a thunderbolt (irresistible force). From Hinduism the concept spread, manifesting as a weapon-shaped ritual item used in Tantric and Tibetan branches of Buddhism.

The terms appearing below are subtypes of vajra. 

* 独鈷杵 (Japanese: [i]tokkosho / dokkosho[/i]): this term appeared in [[Toramaru Shou]]'s "spell card":http://en.touhouwiki.net/wiki/Undefined_Fantastic_Object/Spell_Cards/Stage_5#Spell_Card_71 (Her weapon is not a vajra, though.) 
* 三鈷杵 ([i]sankosho[/i]) 
* 五鈷杵 ([i]gokosho[/i]): used by [[Sowaka-chan]]. 

h4.External links

* "Wikipedia: Vajra":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vajra

title: minna-dietlinde_wilcke
body:
Minna-Dietlinde Wilcke (ミーナ・ディートリンデ・ヴィルケ, Mīna Dītorinde Viruke?) is a Witch of the [[501st Joint Fighter Wing]] attached with the [[Karlsland]] Air Force. She became renowned as the Ace of Spades (スペードのエース, Supēdo no Ēsu), although some also call her by the pet name of Fürstin (フュルスティン, Fyurusutin). Her familiar is the [[wolf]]. 

She is skilled at leading operations and squad management and, rather than pursuing her own individual military gains, she focus on the efficient military performance of the squad as a whole. She also has a tendency to look after her subordinates, which causes some to have a motherly impression about her.

Minna's inherent magic is called Three Dimensional Space Understanding Ability (三次元空間把握能力, Sanjigen Kūkan Haaku Nōryoku). Classified in the perception-lineage, it makes possible to perceive and discern all nearby targets in every direction, sorting out their position, number and classification.

Her ace archetype is "Wolf-Dietrich Wilcke":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolf-Dietrich_Wilcke. Similar to Minna, Wolf-Dietrich bore the nickname "Fürst" amongst his friends and squadmates. 

Due to a scene in the second season she is often drawn with a noteworthy [[ass]].
